Summary:
SPLC is seeking a Senior Data Reporter to lead large-scale data collection and analysis projects to inform investigative reporting on the radical right. The ideal candidate will have deep experience creating compelling data-driven investigative reporting. The Senior Data Reporter will help lead the data analysis planning and reporting for both existing data sets as well as for collecting new data sets.

Primary Job Functions:

Working in close partnership with our research and investigations teams, plan and execute quantitative analyses — and interpret results — for short- and long-form stories and visualizations;
Make phone calls, conduct interviews and do on-the-ground reporting;
Assist fellow reporters with data brainstorming, acquisition, data cleaning, integrity-checking and analysis;
Bulletproof and spot-check data work done by other journalists on the team and in the newsroom;
Assist researchers and developers in collecting data, including FOIA'ing for it, scraping it, cleaning it, analyzing it, and preparing it for publication;
Teach and encourage best practices and newsroom data policies;
Utilize sources, documents, computer-assisted reporting, and other journalistic tools to develop, report, write and produce exclusive accountability stories and investigative projects;
Compile documentation to facilitate ease of fact checking.

Qualifications –

Education and Related Work Experience:

Bachelor's degree in journalism or a quantitative field (statistics, economics) required;
5-7 years of investigative journalism experience with demonstrated results;
Experience working on data projects in a newsroom or experience doing statistical or data-scientific analysis, either in academia or in another research setting;
Excellent interpersonal skills, solid editorial judgment, and the ability to write quickly and cleanly;
A solid understanding of the tools of data analysis, such as database management systems (MongoDB or SQL Server), statistics software (R, Python/pandas), Microsoft Excel, etc;
Have a track record of using data to drive investigative and enterprise reporting, with a commitment to uncompromising accuracy;
Familiarity with online platforms and best social media practices;
Commitment to develop and maintain sources;
Not for profit experience is preferred but not essential.

Knowledge, skills and abilities:

Creative thinking and problem-solving skills;
Excellent research, writing and reporting skills;
Expertise in the radical right;
Strong ability to build trust and credibility with stakeholders across lines of difference;
Proven ability to manage multiple tasks in a fast-paced environment;
Ability to meet deadlines, take initiative, receive constructive feedback, and work autonomously;
Ability to manage multiple projects and deadlines;
Must be able to work in a fast-paced environment with demonstrated ability to manage multiple competing tasks and demands on deadline;
Must be a team player;
Commitment to the mission of the SPLC.

Other Special Considerations:
This job is performed under general office conditions and is not subject to any strenuous physical demands or dangerous conditions.

Disclaimer:
The statements herein are intended to describe the general nature and level of work being performed by the employee in this position. These statements are not intended to be construed as an exhaustive list of all responsibilities, duties, and skills required of a person in this position.

An Equal-Opportunity Employer with a Commitment to Diversity

Southern Poverty Law Center (SPLC) is proud to be an equal opportunity employer, and as an organization committed to diversity and the perspective of all voices, we consider applicants equally of race, gender, gender identity, color, sexual orientation, religion, marital status, disability, political affiliation, national origin, or prior record of arrest or conviction.

The objectives of the project are as follows:
Objective #1: Public information and data on government budgets and public works processed, analyzed, and published by journalists and civil society organization (CSO) actors
Objective #2: Data-driven projects facilitating access to information and investigative journalism produced
Objective #3: Anti-corruption policies recommended
Objective #4: Stories produced and shared across national, subnational, and international networks of investigative journalists (IJ)
Objective #5: State-level newsrooms adopt new sustainable business models and diversify revenue sources
Responsibilities
The monitoring and evaluation specialist will support ICFJ’s five-year USAID-sponsored “The Mexico Border Investigative Reporting Hub” program. To do this, the consultant will engage with ICFJ HQ program staff, project partners, and participating journalists to undertake the following tasks:
Participate in one orientation/kick-off meeting in Washington, D.C. or virtually with ICFJ HQ program staff;
Gather and consolidate the impact of investigative projects and fellowships (up to an estimated 50 investigative projects per year) and exchange fellowships;
Design evaluation tools like pre-and post-surveys to gather information on knowledge gained for the following trainings and workshops:
A total of 5 conferences on investigative journalism (1 per year);
A total of 1 online six-week training courses on data-driven journalism;
A total of 5 three-day local workshops on digital, mobile security and developing investigative projects;
A total of 3 Data Bootcamps focused on the development and design of data-driven projects that can receive seed funding;
Measure the use and proliferation of ICFJ’s secure online platform (a platform used to better protect journalists against emergent threats) and dashboard (a platform with searchable resources, databases, and information that can serve to inform journalists’ investigations);
Provide basic metrics on project data, at the request of ICFJ program staff;
Prepare high-quality quarterly reports highlighting the compiled data, utilizing information provided by ICFJ HQ program staff, project partners, and participating journalists.
Timeframe
The consultancy should begin in October 2018 and will go until June 2023, based on effective completion of objectives, as determined by ICFJ headquarters program staff. Performance will be reviewed on an annual basis.
Location
This position can be based in any location. The bulk of the work can be done remotely, via Skype, email, etc. The consultancy will report to the Deputy Vice-President of Programs in the Washington, DC headquarters, but will be in close contact with all assigned ICFJ staff working on the program.
Required skills and qualifications
Both individuals and companies are encouraged to apply.
Working bilingual capability in Spanish and English (Applications without this will NOT be considered);
Experience working with USAID, State Department, or government grants;
Familiarity with data gathering and visualization tools;
8-12 years of proven experience conducting monitoring and evaluation focused on outcome-level indicators.
Apply here.
